## Why This Is Asked

Tests ability to diagnose and execute a safe, low-downtime rollout when a new image introduces instability. Focuses on rollout metadata, readiness, and quick rollback.

## Key Concepts

- Kubernetes Deployments and ReplicaSets
- Rollout history and remediation
- Readiness/Liveness probes and startup checks
- Canary/blue-green deployment patterns for safety
- Rollback with kubectl rollout undo
- Latency validation under load

## Code Example

```javascript
// Node.js pseudo-code using Kubernetes client to check rollout and query metrics
const k8s = require('@kubernetes/client-node');
const kc = new k8s.KubeConfig();
kc.loadFromDefault();
const apps = kc.makeApiClient(k8s.AppsV1Api);
async function checkRollout(name, ns='default') {
  const r = await apps.readNamespacedDeployment(name, ns);
  console.log(r.body.status);
}
checkRollout('orders-api', 'kcsa-prod');
```

## Follow-up Questions

- How would you explicitly structure a canary deployment to guarantee no more than 10% traffic to the new version while monitoring SLI/SLOs?
- What metrics and alerts would you rely on to detect regressions during rollout and trigger rollback automatically?

## Why This Is Asked
The goal is to assess practical pagination design and data modeling skills on a tiny API layer, including correctness and testability.

## Key Concepts
- Pagination parameters validation
- Indexed queries and ORDER BY performance
- Edge-case handling and test coverage

## Code Example

```javascript
function paginate(items, limit, offset) {
  if (limit <= 0 || offset < 0) throw new Error("Invalid pagination params");
  const total = items.length;
  const paged = items.slice(offset, offset + limit);
  return { total, items: paged };
}
```

## Follow-up Questions
- How would you test pagination with 10k+ records and caching?
- How would you adapt logic for distributed databases or replicas?
